# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abstract-interpretation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] In computer science, **abstract interpretation** is a theory of sound approximation of the semantics of computer programs, based on monotonic functions over ordered sets, especially lattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] It can be viewed as a partial execution of a computer program which gains information about its semantics (e.g., control-flow, data-flow) without performing all the calculations.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Abstract interpretation was formalized by the French computer scientist working couple Patrick Cousot and Radhia Cousot in the late 1970s.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] This section illustrates abstract interpretation by means of real-world, non-computing examples.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Consider the people in a conference room.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Assume a unique identifier for each person in the room, like a social security number in the United States.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] To prove that someone is not present, all one needs to do is see if their social security number is not on the list.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Since two different people cannot have the same number, it is possible to prove or disprove the presence of a participant simply by looking up their number.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] However it is possible that only the names of attendees were registered.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] If the name of a person is not found in the list, we may safely conclude that that person was not present; but if it is, we cannot conclude definitely without further inquiries, due to the possibility of homonyms (for example, two people named John Smith).
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Note that this imprecise information will still be adequate for most purposes, because homonyms are rare in practice.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] However, in all rigor, we cannot say for sure that somebody was present in the room; all we can say is that they were *possibly* here.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] If the person we are looking up is a criminal, we will issue an *alarm*; but there is of course the possibility of issuing a *false alarm*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Similar phenomena will occur in the analysis of programs.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] If we are only interested in some specific information, say, "was there a person of age n in the room?", keeping a list of all names and dates of births is unnecessary.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] We may safely and without loss of precision restrict ourselves to keeping a list of the participants' ages.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] If this is already too much to handle, we might keep only the age of the youngest, m and oldest person, M .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] If the question is about an age strictly lower than m or strictly higher than M , then we may safely respond that no such participant was present.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Otherwise, we may only be able to say that we do not know.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] In the case of computing, concrete, precise information is in general not computable within finite time and memory (see Rice's theorem and the halting problem).
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] One crucial requirement is to add enough vagueness so as to make problems manageable while still retaining enough precision for answering the important questions (such as "might the program crash?").
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Given a programming or specification language, abstract interpretation consists of giving several semantics linked by relations of abstraction.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] A semantics is a mathematical characterization of a possible behavior of the program.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] The most precise semantics, describing very closely the actual execution of the program, are called the *concrete semantics*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] More abstract semantics are then derived; for instance, one may consider only the set of reachable states in the executions (which amounts to considering the last states in finite traces).
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] The goal of static analysis is to derive a computable semantic interpretation at some point.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] For instance, one may choose to represent the state of a program manipulating integer variables by forgetting the actual values of the variables and only keeping their signs (+, − or 0).
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] For some elementary operations, such as multiplication, such an abstraction does not lose any precision: to get the sign of a product, it is sufficient to know the sign of the operands.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] For some other operations, the abstraction may lose precision: for instance, it is impossible to know the sign of a sum whose operands are respectively positive and negative.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Sometimes a loss of precision is necessary to make the semantics decidable (see Rice's theorem and the halting problem).
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] In general, there is a compromise to be made between the precision of the analysis and its decidability (computability), or tractability (computational cost).
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] In practice the abstractions that are defined are tailored to both the program properties one desires to analyze, and to the set of target programs.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] The first large scale automated analysis of computer programs with abstract interpretation was motivated by the accident that resulted in the destruction of the first flight of the Ariane 5 rocket in 1996.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Let L be an ordered set, called *concrete set*, and let $L'$ be another ordered set, called *abstract set*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] These two sets are related to each other by defining total functions that map elements from one to the other.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] A function $\alpha$ is called an *abstraction function* if it maps an element x in the concrete set L to an element $\alpha (x)$ in the abstract set $L'$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] That is, element $\alpha (x)$ in $L'$ is the *abstraction* of x in L .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] A function $\gamma$ is called a *concretization function* if it maps an element $x'$ in the abstract set $L'$ to an element $\gamma (x')$ in the concrete set L .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] That is, element $\gamma (x')$ in L is a *concretization* of $x'$ in $L'$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] The concrete semantics f is a monotonic function from $L_{1}$ to $L_{2}$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Program semantics are generally described using fixed points in the presence of loops or recursive procedures.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Suppose that L is a complete lattice and let f be a monotonic function from L into L .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Then, any $x'$ such that $f(x')\leq x'$ is an abstraction of the least fixed-point of f , which exists, according to the Knaster–Tarski theorem.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] The difficulty is now to obtain such an $x'$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] In some cases, it is possible to define abstractions using Galois connections $(\alpha ,\gamma )$ where $\alpha$ is from L to $L'$ and $\gamma$ is from $L'$ to L .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] This supposes the existence of best abstractions, which is not necessarily the case.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] For instance, if we abstract sets of couples $(x,y)$ of real numbers by enclosing convex polyhedra, there is no optimal abstraction to the disc defined by $x^{2}+y^{2}\leq 1$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] One can assign to each variable x available at a given program point an interval $[L_{x},H_{x}]$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] A state assigning the value $v(x)$ to variable x will be a concretization of these intervals if, for all x , we have $v(x)\in [L_{x},H_{x}]$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] More complex formulas can be derived for multiplication, division, etc., yielding so-called interval arithmetics.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] With reasonable arithmetic types, the result for z should be zero.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] But if we do interval arithmetic starting from x in [0, 1], one gets z in [−1, +1].
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] While each of the operations taken individually was exactly abstracted, their composition isn't.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] The problem is evident: we did not keep track of the equality relationship between x and y; actually, this domain of intervals does not take into account any relationships between variables, and is thus a *non-relational domain*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Non-relational domains tend to be fast and simple to implement, but imprecise.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] and combinations thereof (such as the reduced product, cf. right picture).
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] When one chooses an abstract domain, one typically has to strike a balance between keeping fine-grained relationships, and high computational costs.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] There are several abstract domains suitable for various analyses of such variables.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] The *bitfield domain* treats each bit in a machine word separately, i.e., a word of width *n* is treated as an array of *n* abstract values.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] Further domains include the *signed interval domain* and the *unsigned interval domain*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] All three of these domains support forwards and backwards abstract operators for common operations such as addition, shifts, xor, and multiplication.
[src:abstract-interpretation/abstract-interpretation] These domains can be combined using the reduced product.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] In mathematics, a **complete lattice** is a partially ordered set in which all subsets have both a supremum (join) and an infimum (meet).
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] A **conditionally complete lattice** satisfies at least one of these properties for bounded and nonempty subsets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] For comparison, in a general lattice, only *pairs* of elements need to have a supremum and an infimum.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Every non-empty finite lattice is complete, but infinite lattices may be incomplete.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Complete lattices appear in many applications in mathematics and computer science.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Both order theory and universal algebra study them as a special class of lattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Complete lattices must not be confused with complete partial orders (CPOs), a more general class of partially ordered sets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] More specific complete lattices are complete Boolean algebras and complete Heyting algebras (locales).
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] A *complete lattice* is a partially ordered set (*L*, ≤) such that every subset *A* of *L* has both a greatest lower bound (the infimum, or *meet*) and a least upper bound (the supremum, or *join*) in (*L*, ≤).
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The *meet* is denoted by $\bigwedge A$ , and the *join* by $\bigvee A$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] In the special case where *A* is the empty set, the meet of *A* is the greatest element of *L*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Likewise, the join of the empty set is the least element of *L*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Then, complete lattices form a special class of bounded lattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] A sublattice *M* of a complete lattice *L* is called a *complete sublattice* of *L* if for every subset *A* of *M* the elements $\bigwedge A$ and $\bigvee A$ , as defined in *L*, are actually in *M*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] If the above requirement is lessened to require only non-empty meet and joins to be in *M*, the sublattice *M* is called a *closed sublattice* of *L*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The terms *complete meet-semilattice* or *complete join-semilattice* is another way to refer to complete lattices since arbitrary meets can be expressed in terms of arbitrary joins and vice versa (for details, see completeness).
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Another usage of "complete meet-semilattice" refers to a meet-semilattice that is bounded complete and a complete partial order.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] This concept is arguably the "most complete" notion of a meet-semilattice that is not yet a lattice (in fact, only the top element may be missing).
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] See semilattices for further discussion between both definitions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] A complete lattice *L* is said to be locally finite if the supremum of any infinite subset is equal to the supremal element.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Denoting this supremal element "1", the condition is equivalently that the set $\{y\in L~|~y\leq x\}\,\!$ is finite for any $1\neq x\in L$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] This notation may clash with other notation, as in the case of the lattice (**N**, |), i.e., the non-negative integers ordered by divisibility.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] In this locally finite lattice, the infimal element denoted "0" for the lattice theory is the number 1 in the set **N** and the supremal element denoted "1" for the lattice theory is the number 0 in the set **N**.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The traditional morphisms between complete lattices, taking the complete lattices as the objects of a category, are the *complete homomorphisms* (or *complete lattice homomorphisms*).
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] These are characterized as functions that preserve all joins and all meets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Such functions are automatically monotonic, but the condition of being a complete homomorphism is in fact much more specific.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] For this reason, it can be useful to consider weaker notions of morphisms, such as those that are only required to preserve all joins (giving a category **Sup**) or all meets (giving a category **Inf**), which are indeed inequivalent conditions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] These notions may also be considered as homomorphisms of complete meet-semilattices or complete join-semilattices, respectively.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Furthermore, morphisms that preserve all joins are equivalently characterized as the *lower adjoint* part of a unique Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] where *f* is called the *lower adjoint* and *g* is called the *upper adjoint*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] By the adjoint functor theorem, a monotone map between any pair of complete lattices preserves all joins if and only if it is a lower adjoint and preserves all meets if and only if it is an upper adjoint.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] As such, each join-preserving morphism determines a unique *upper adjoint* in the inverse direction that preserves all meets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Hence, considering complete lattices with complete semilattice morphisms (of either type, join-preserving or meet-preserving) boils down to considering Galois connections as one's lattice morphisms.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] A particularly important class of special cases arises between lattices of subsets of *X* and *Y*, i.e., the power sets ⁠ $P(X)$ ⁠ and ⁠ $P(Y)$ ⁠, given a function ⁠ f ⁠ from *X* to *Y*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] In these cases, the direct image and inverse image maps induced by ⁠ f ⁠ between the power sets are upper and lower adjoints to each other, respectively.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The construction of free objects depends on the chosen class of morphisms.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Functions that preserve all joins (i.e. lower adjoints of Galois connections) are called *free complete join-semilattices*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] This means that $f(s)=f^{\circ }(i(s))$ for every element s of S , and that $f^{\circ }$ is the only morphism with this property.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Hence, there is a functor from the category of sets and functions to the category of complete lattices and join-preserving functions which is left adjoint to the forgetful functor from complete lattices to their underlying sets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Free complete lattices can thus be constructed such that the complete lattice generated by some set *S* is just the powerset $2^{S}$ , the set of all subsets of *S* ordered by subset inclusion.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The required unit $i:S\rightarrow 2^{S}$ maps any element s of S to the singleton set $\{s\}$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Then $f^{\circ }$ transforms unions into suprema and thus preserves joins.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] These considerations also yield a free construction for morphisms that preserve meets instead of joins (i.e. upper adjoints of Galois connections).
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The above can be dualized: free objects are given as powersets ordered by reverse inclusion, such that set union provides the meet operation, and the function $f^{\circ }$ is defined in terms of meets instead of joins.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The result of this construction is known as a *free complete meet-semilattice*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] It can be noted that these free constructions extend those that are used to obtain free semilattices, where finite sets need to be considered.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The situation for complete lattices with complete homomorphisms is more intricate.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] In fact, free complete lattices generally do not exist.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Of course, one can formulate a word problem similar to the one for the case of lattices, but the collection of all possible words (or "terms") in this case would be a proper class, because arbitrary meets and joins comprise operations for argument sets of every cardinality.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] This property in itself is not a problem: as the case of free complete semilattices above shows, it can well be that the solution of the word problem leaves only a set of equivalence classes.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] In other words, it is possible that the proper classes of all terms have the same meaning and are thus identified in the free construction.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] However, the equivalence classes for the word problem of complete lattices are "too small," such that the free complete lattice would still be a proper class, which is not allowed.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Now, one might still hope that there are some useful cases where the set of generators is sufficiently small for a free, complete lattice to exist.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] A proof of this statement is given by Johnstone.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The original argument is attributed to Alfred W.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Hales; see also the article on free lattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] If a complete lattice is freely generated from a given *poset* used in place of the set of generators considered above, then one speaks of a *completion* of the poset.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The definition of the result of this operation is similar to the above definition of free objects, where "sets" and "functions" are replaced by "posets" and "monotone mappings".
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Likewise, one can describe the completion process as a functor from the category of posets with monotone functions to some category of complete lattices with appropriate morphisms that are left adjoint to the forgetful functor in the converse direction.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] As long as one considers meet- or join-preserving functions as morphisms, this can easily be achieved through the so-called Dedekind–MacNeille completion.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] For this process, elements of the poset are mapped to (Dedekind-) *cuts*, which can then be mapped to the underlying posets of arbitrary complete lattices in much the same way as done for sets and free complete (semi-) lattices above.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The aforementioned result that free complete lattices do not exist entails that an according free construction from a poset is not possible either.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] This is easily seen by considering posets with a discrete order, where every element only relates to itself.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] These are exactly the free posets on an underlying set.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Would there be a free construction of complete lattices from posets, then both constructions could be composed, which contradicts the negative result above.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Birkhoff's book *Lattice Theory* contains a very useful representation method.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] It associates a complete lattice to any binary relation between two sets by constructing a Galois connection from the relation, which then leads to two dually isomorphic closure systems.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Closure systems are intersection-closed families of sets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] When ordered by the subset relation ⊆, they are complete lattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] A special instance of Birkhoff's construction starts from an arbitrary poset *(P,≤)* and constructs the Galois connection from the order relation ≤ between *P* and itself.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The resulting complete lattice is the Dedekind-MacNeille completion.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] When this completion is applied to a poset that already is a complete lattice, then the result is isomorphic to the original one.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Thus, we immediately find that every complete lattice is represented by Birkhoff's method, up to isomorphism.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The construction is utilized in formal concept analysis, where one represents real-word data by binary relations (called *formal contexts*) and uses the associated complete lattices (called *concept lattices*) for data analysis.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The mathematics behind formal concept analysis therefore is the theory of complete lattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Another representation is obtained as follows: A subset of a complete lattice is itself a complete lattice (when ordered with the induced order) if and only if it is the image of an increasing and idempotent (but not necessarily extensive) self-map.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] The identity mapping has these two properties.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] Besides the previous representation results, there are some other statements that can be made about complete lattices, or that take a particularly simple form in this case.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] An example is the Knaster–Tarski theorem, which states that the set of fixed points of a monotone function on a complete lattice is again a complete lattice.
[src:abstract-interpretation/complete-lattice] This is easily seen to be a generalization of the above observation about the images of increasing and idempotent functions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] In numerical analysis, **fixed-point iteration** is a method of computing fixed points of a function.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] More generally, the function f can be defined on any metric space with values in that same space.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] An *attracting fixed point* of a function *f* is a fixed point *x*fix of *f* with a neighborhood *U* of "close enough" points around *x*fix such that for any value of x in *U*, the fixed-point iteration sequence $x,\ f(x),\ f(f(x)),\ f(f(f(x))),\dots$ is contained in *U* and converges to *x*fix.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] The basin of attraction of *x*fix is the largest such neighborhood *U*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] The natural cosine function ("natural" means in radians, not degrees or other units) has exactly one fixed point, and that fixed point is attracting.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] In this case, "close enough" is not a stringent criterion at all—to demonstrate this, start with *any* real number and repeatedly press the *cos* key on a calculator (checking first that the calculator is in "radians" mode).
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] It eventually converges to the Dottie number (about 0.739085133), which is a fixed point.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] That is where the graph of the cosine function intersects the line $y=x$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] For example, 0 is a fixed point of the function *f*(*x*) = 2*x*, but iteration of this function for any value other than zero rapidly diverges.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] We say that the fixed point of $f(x)=2x$ is repelling.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] An attracting fixed point is said to be a *stable fixed point* if it is also Lyapunov stable.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] A fixed point is said to be a *neutrally stable fixed point* if it is Lyapunov stable but not attracting.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] The center of a linear homogeneous differential equation of the second order is an example of a neutrally stable fixed point.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Multiple attracting points can be collected in an *attracting fixed set*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] The Banach fixed-point theorem gives a sufficient condition for the existence of attracting fixed points.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] A contraction mapping function f defined on a complete metric space has precisely one fixed point, and the fixed-point iteration is attracted towards that fixed point for any initial guess $x_{0}$ in the domain of the function.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Common special cases are that (1) f is defined on the real line with real values and is Lipschitz continuous with Lipschitz constant $L<1$ , and (2) the function *f* is continuously differentiable in an open neighbourhood of a fixed point *x*fix, and $|f'(x_{\text{fix}})|<1$ .
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Although there are other fixed-point theorems, this one in particular is very useful because not all fixed-points are attractive.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] When constructing a fixed-point iteration, it is very important to make sure it converges to the fixed point.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] We can usually use the Banach fixed-point theorem to show that the fixed point is attractive.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Attracting fixed points are a special case of a wider mathematical concept of attractors.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Fixed-point iterations are a discrete dynamical system on one variable.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Bifurcation theory studies dynamical systems and classifies various behaviors such as attracting fixed points, periodic orbits, or strange attractors.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] In computational mathematics, an iterative method is a mathematical procedure that uses an initial value to generate a sequence of improving approximate solutions for a class of problems, in which the n-th approximation is derived from the previous ones.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Convergent fixed-point iterations are mathematically rigorous formalizations of iterative methods.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] The speed of convergence of the iteration sequence can be increased by using a convergence acceleration method such as Anderson acceleration and Aitken's delta-squared process.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] The application of Aitken's method to fixed-point iteration is known as Steffensen's method, and it can be shown that Steffensen's method yields a rate of convergence that is at least quadratic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] The term *chaos game* refers to a method of generating the fixed point of any iterated function system (IFS).
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Starting with any point *x*0, successive iterations are formed as *x**k*+1 = *f**r*(*x**k*), where *f**r* is a member of the given IFS randomly selected for each iteration.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Hence the chaos game is a randomized fixed-point iteration.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] The chaos game allows plotting the general shape of a fractal such as the Sierpinski triangle by repeating the iterative process a large number of times.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] More mathematically, the iterations converge to the fixed point of the IFS.
[src:abstract-interpretation/fixed-point-iteration] Whenever *x*0 belongs to the attractor of the IFS, all iterations *x**k* stay inside the attractor and, with probability 1, form a dense set in the latter.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In mathematics, especially in order theory, a **Galois connection** is a particular correspondence (typically) between two partially ordered sets (posets).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Galois connections find applications in various mathematical theories.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] They generalize the fundamental theorem of Galois theory about the correspondence between subgroups and subfields, discovered by the French mathematician Évariste Galois.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] A Galois connection can also be defined on preordered sets or classes; this article presents the common case of posets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The literature contains two closely related notions of "Galois connection".
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In this article, we will refer to them as **(monotone) Galois connections** and **antitone Galois connections**.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] A Galois connection is rather weak compared to an order isomorphism between the involved posets, but every Galois connection gives rise to an isomorphism of certain sub-posets, as will be explained below.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The term **Galois correspondence** is sometimes used to mean a bijective *Galois connection*; this is simply an order isomorphism (or dual order isomorphism, depending on whether we take monotone or antitone Galois connections).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Let (*A*, ≤) and (*B*, ≤) be two partially ordered sets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In this situation, F is called the **lower adjoint** of G and G is called the **upper adjoint** of *F*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Mnemonically, the upper/lower terminology refers to where the function application appears relative to ≤.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The term "adjoint" refers to the fact that monotone Galois connections are special cases of pairs of adjoint functors in category theory as discussed further below.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Other terminology encountered here is **left adjoint** (respectively **right adjoint**) for the lower (respectively upper) adjoint.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] A consequence of this is that if F or G is bijective then each is the inverse of the other, i.e.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Given a Galois connection with lower adjoint F and upper adjoint G, we can consider the compositions *GF* : *A* → *A*, known as the associated closure operator, and *FG* : *B* → *B*, known as the associated kernel operator.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Both are monotone and idempotent, and we have *a* ≤ *GF*(*a*) for all a in A and *FG*(*b*) ≤ *b* for all b in B.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] A **Galois insertion** of B into A is a Galois connection in which the kernel operator FG is the identity on B, and hence G is an order isomorphism of B onto the set of closed elements GF [A] of A.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The above definition is common in many applications today, and prominent in lattice and domain theory.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] However the original notion in Galois theory is slightly different.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The symmetry of F and G in this version erases the distinction between upper and lower, and the two functions are then called **polarities** rather than adjoints.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The compositions *GF* : *A* → *A* and *FG* : *B* → *B* are the associated closure operators; they are monotone idempotent maps with the property *a* ≤ *GF*(*a*) for all a in A and *b* ≤ *FG*(*b*) for all b in B.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The implications of the two definitions of Galois connections are very similar, since an antitone Galois connection between A and B is just a monotone Galois connection between A and the order dual *B*op of B.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] All of the below statements on Galois connections can thus easily be converted into statements about antitone Galois connections.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The bijection of a pair of functions $f:X\to Y$ and $g:Y\to X,$ each other's inverse, forms a (trivial) Galois connection, as follows.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Because the equality relation is reflexive, transitive and antisymmetric, it is, trivially, a partial order, making $(X,=)$ and $(Y,=)$ partially ordered sets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Since $f(x)=y$ if and only if $x=g(y),$ we have a Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The embedding of integers is customarily done implicitly, but to show the Galois connection we make it explicit.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] This is valid because the variable n is restricted to the integers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The well-known properties of the floor function, such as $\lfloor x+n\rfloor =\lfloor x\rfloor +n,$ can be derived by elementary reasoning from this Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] For an order-theoretic example, let U be some set, and let A and B both be the power set of U, ordered by inclusion.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Then the maps F and G, where *F*(*M* ) = *L* ∩ *M*, and *G*(*N* ) = *N* ∪ (*U* \ *L*), form a monotone Galois connection, with F being the lower adjoint.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] A similar Galois connection whose lower adjoint is given by the meet (infimum) operation can be found in any Heyting algebra.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Especially, it is present in any Boolean algebra, where the two mappings can be described by *F*(*x*) = (*a* ∧ *x*) and *G*(*y*) = (*y* ∨ ¬*a*) = (*a* ⇒ *y*).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In logical terms: "implication from a" is the upper adjoint of "conjunction with a".
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Further interesting examples for Galois connections are described in the article on completeness properties.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Roughly speaking, the usual functions ∨ and ∧ are lower and upper adjoints to the diagonal map *X* → *X* × *X*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The least and greatest elements of a partial order are given by lower and upper adjoints to the unique function *X* → {1}.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Going further, even complete lattices can be characterized by the existence of suitable adjoints.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] These considerations give some impression of the ubiquity of Galois connections in order theory.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Let G act transitively on X and pick some point x in X.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Further, let ${\mathcal {G}}$ consist of the subgroups of G containing the stabilizer of x.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] is a monotone, one-to-one Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] As a corollary, one can establish that doubly transitive actions have no blocks other than the trivial ones (singletons or the whole of X): this follows from the stabilizers being maximal in G in that case.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] See Doubly transitive group for further discussion.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] If *f* : *X* → *Y* is a function, then for any subset M of X we can form the image *F*(*M* ) = *f* *M* = { *f* (*m*) | *m* ∈ *M*} and for any subset N of Y we can form the inverse image *G*(*N* ) = *f* −1*N* = {*x* ∈ *X* | *f* (*x*) ∈ *N*}.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Then F and G form a monotone Galois connection between the power set of X and the power set of Y, both ordered by inclusion ⊆.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] There is a further adjoint pair in this situation: for a subset M of X, define *H*(*M*) = {*y* ∈ *Y* | *f* −1{*y*} ⊆ *M*}.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Then G and H form a monotone Galois connection between the power set of Y and the power set of X.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In the first Galois connection, G is the upper adjoint, while in the second Galois connection it serves as the lower adjoint.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In the case of a quotient map between algebraic objects (such as groups), this connection is called the lattice theorem: subgroups of G connect to subgroups of *G*/*N*, and the closure operator on subgroups of G is given by *H* = *HN*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Pick some mathematical object X that has an underlying set, for instance a group, ring, vector space, etc.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] For any subset S of X, let *F*(*S* ) be the smallest subobject of X that contains S, i.e. the subgroup, subring or subspace generated by S.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] For any subobject U of X, let *G*(*U* ) be the underlying set of U.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] (We can even take X to be a topological space, let *F*(*S* ) the closure of S, and take as "subobjects of X" the closed subsets of X.) Now F and G form a monotone Galois connection between subsets of X and subobjects of X, if both are ordered by inclusion.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] A very general comment of William Lawvere is that *syntax and semantics* are adjoint: take A to be the set of all logical theories (axiomatizations) reverse ordered by strength, and B the power set of the set of all mathematical structures.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] We can then say that S is a subset of Mod(*T* ) if and only if Th(*S* ) logically entails T: the "semantics functor" Mod and the "syntax functor" Th form a monotone Galois connection, with semantics being the upper adjoint.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The motivating example comes from Galois theory: suppose *L*/*K* is a field extension.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Let A be the set of all subfields of L that contain K, ordered by inclusion ⊆.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] If E is such a subfield, write Gal(*L*/*E*) for the group of field automorphisms of L that hold E fixed.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Let B be the set of subgroups of Gal(*L*/*K*), ordered by inclusion ⊆.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] For such a subgroup G, define Fix(*G*) to be the field consisting of all elements of L that are held fixed by all elements of G.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Then the maps *E* ↦ Gal(*L*/*E*) and *G* ↦ Fix(*G*) form an antitone Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Analogously, given a path-connected topological space X, there is an antitone Galois connection between subgroups of the fundamental group *π*1(*X*) and path-connected covering spaces of X.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In particular, if X is semi-locally simply connected, then for every subgroup G of *π*1(*X*), there is a covering space with G as its fundamental group.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Given an inner product space V, we can form the orthogonal complement *F*(*X* ) of any subspace X of V.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] This yields an antitone Galois connection between the set of subspaces of V and itself, ordered by inclusion; both polarities are equal to F.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Given a vector space V and a subset X of V we can define its annihilator *F*(*X* ), consisting of all elements of the dual space *V* ∗ of V that vanish on X.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] This gives an antitone Galois connection between the subsets of V and the subsets of *V* ∗.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In algebraic geometry, the relation between sets of polynomials and their zero sets is an antitone Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Fix a natural number n and a field K and let A be the set of all subsets of the polynomial ring *K*[*X*1, ..., *Xn*] ordered by inclusion ⊆, and let B be the set of all subsets of *K* *n* ordered by inclusion ⊆.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] the set of common zeros of the polynomials in S.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Then V and *I* form an antitone Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The closure on *K* *n* is the closure in the Zariski topology, and if the field K is algebraically closed, then the closure on the polynomial ring is the radical of ideal generated by S.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] More generally, given a commutative ring R (not necessarily a polynomial ring), there is an antitone Galois connection between radical ideals in the ring and Zariski closed subsets of the affine variety Spec(*R*).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] More generally, there is an antitone Galois connection between ideals in the ring and subschemes of the corresponding affine variety.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Suppose X and Y are arbitrary sets and a binary relation R over X and Y is given.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Then F and G yield an antitone Galois connection between the power sets of X and Y, both ordered by inclusion ⊆.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Up to isomorphism *all* antitone Galois connections between power sets arise in this way.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] This follows from the "Basic Theorem on Concept Lattices".
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Theory and applications of Galois connections arising from binary relations are studied in formal concept analysis.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] That field uses Galois connections for mathematical data analysis.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Many algorithms for Galois connections can be found in the respective literature, e.g., in.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The general concept lattice in its primitive version incorporates both the monotone and antitone Galois connections to furnish its upper and lower bounds of nodes for the concept lattice, respectively.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In the following, we consider a (monotone) Galois connection *f* = ( *f* ∗, *f*∗), where *f* ∗ : *A* → *B* is the lower adjoint as introduced above.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Some helpful and instructive basic properties can be obtained immediately.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] By the defining property of Galois connections, *f* ∗(*x*) ≤ *f* ∗(*x*) is equivalent to *x* ≤ *f*∗( *f* ∗(*x*)), for all x in A.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] By a similar reasoning (or just by applying the duality principle for order theory), one finds that *f* ∗( *f*∗(*y*)) ≤ *y*, for all y in B.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] These properties can be described by saying the composite *f* ∗∘ *f*∗ is *deflationary*, while *f*∗∘ *f* ∗ is *inflationary* (or *extensive*).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Applying the basic property of Galois connections, one can now conclude that *f* ∗(*x*) ≤ *f* ∗(*y*).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] But this just shows that *f* ∗ preserves the order of any two elements, i.e. it is monotone.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Again, a similar reasoning yields monotonicity of *f*∗.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Thus monotonicity does not have to be included in the definition explicitly.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] However, mentioning monotonicity helps to avoid confusion about the two alternative notions of Galois connections.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Another basic property of Galois connections is the fact that *f*∗( *f* ∗( *f*∗(*x*))) = *f*∗(*x*), for all x in B.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] because *f*∗∘ *f* ∗ is inflationary as shown above.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] It can be shown (see Blyth or Erné for proofs) that a function *f* is a lower (respectively upper) adjoint if and only if *f* is a residuated mapping (respectively residual mapping).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Therefore, the notion of residuated mapping and monotone Galois connection are essentially the same.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The above findings can be summarized as follows: for a Galois connection, the composite *f*∗∘ *f* ∗ is monotone (being the composite of monotone functions), inflationary, and idempotent.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] This states that *f*∗∘ *f* ∗ is in fact a closure operator on A.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Dually, *f* ∗∘ *f*∗ is monotone, deflationary, and idempotent.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Such mappings are sometimes called **kernel operators**.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In the context of frames and locales, the composite *f*∗∘ *f* ∗ is called the **nucleus** induced by *f* .
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Nuclei induce frame homomorphisms; a subset of a locale is called a sublocale if it is given by a nucleus.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Conversely, any closure operator c on some poset A gives rise to the Galois connection with lower adjoint *f* ∗ being just the corestriction of c to the image of c (i.e. as a surjective mapping the closure system *c*(*A*)).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The upper adjoint *f*∗ is then given by the inclusion of *c*(*A*) into A, that maps each closed element to itself, considered as an element of A.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In this way, closure operators and Galois connections are seen to be closely related, each specifying an instance of the other.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Similar conclusions hold true for kernel operators.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The above considerations also show that closed elements of A (elements x with *f*∗( *f* ∗(*x*)) = *x*) are mapped to elements within the range of the kernel operator *f* ∗∘ *f*∗, and vice versa.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Another important property of Galois connections is that lower adjoints preserve all suprema that exist within their domain.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Dually, upper adjoints preserve all existing infima.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] From these properties, one can also conclude monotonicity of the adjoints immediately.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The adjoint functor theorem for order theory states that the converse implication is also valid in certain cases: especially, any mapping between complete lattices that preserves all suprema is the lower adjoint of a Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In this situation, an important feature of Galois connections is that one adjoint uniquely determines the other.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Hence one can strengthen the above statement to guarantee that any supremum-preserving map between complete lattices is the lower adjoint of a unique Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The main property to derive this uniqueness is the following: For every x in A, *f* ∗(*x*) is the least element y of B such that *x* ≤ *f*∗(*y*).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Dually, for every y in B, *f*∗(*y*) is the greatest x in A such that *f* ∗(*x*) ≤ *y*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] The existence of a certain Galois connection now implies the existence of the respective least or greatest elements, no matter whether the corresponding posets satisfy any completeness properties.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Thus, when one upper adjoint of a Galois connection is given, the other upper adjoint can be defined via this same property.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] On the other hand, some monotone function *f* is a lower adjoint if and only if each set of the form {*x* ∈ *A* | *f* (*x*) ≤ *b*}, for b in B, contains a greatest element.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Again, this can be dualized for the upper adjoint.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Galois connections also provide an interesting class of mappings between posets which can be used to obtain categories of posets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Especially, it is possible to compose Galois connections: given Galois connections ( *f* ∗, *f*∗) between posets A and B and (*g*∗, *g*∗) between B and C, the composite (*g*∗ ∘ *f* ∗, *f*∗ ∘ *g*∗) is also a Galois connection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] When considering categories of complete lattices, this can be simplified to considering just mappings preserving all suprema (or, alternatively, infima).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Mapping complete lattices to their duals, these categories display auto duality, that are quite fundamental for obtaining other duality theorems.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] More special kinds of morphisms that induce adjoint mappings in the other direction are the morphisms usually considered for frames (or locales).
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Every partially ordered set can be viewed as a category in a natural way: there is a unique morphism from *x* to *y* if and only if *x* ≤ *y*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] A monotone Galois connection is then nothing but a pair of adjoint functors between two categories that arise from partially ordered sets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] In this context, the upper adjoint is the *right adjoint* while the lower adjoint is the *left adjoint*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] However, this terminology is avoided for Galois connections, since there was a time when posets were transformed into categories in a dual fashion, i.e. with morphisms pointing in the opposite direction.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] This led to a complementary notation concerning left and right adjoints, which today is ambiguous.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Let $f:L\rightarrow P$ be a monotone function from a complete lattice to a poset.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] And similarly: f preserves all join if and only if f has an right adjoint.
[src:abstract-interpretation/galois-connection] Galois connections may be used to describe many forms of abstraction in the theory of abstract interpretation of programming languages.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Mathematically, instead of working with an uncertain real-valued variable x, interval arithmetic works with an interval [*a*, *b*] that defines the range of values that x can have.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In other words, any value of the variable x lies in the closed interval between a and b.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A function f, when applied to x, produces an interval [*c*, *d*] which includes all the possible values for *f*(*x*) for all x ∈ [*a*, *b*].
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The latter often arise from measurement errors and tolerances for components or due to limits on computational accuracy.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic also helps find guaranteed solutions to equations (such as differential equations) and optimization problems.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The main objective of interval arithmetic is to provide a simple way of calculating upper and lower bounds of a function's range in one or more variables.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] These endpoints are not necessarily the true supremum or infimum of a range since the precise calculation of those values can be difficult or impossible; the bounds only need to contain the function's range as a subset.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] With one of a, b infinite, the interval would be an unbounded interval; with both infinite, the interval would be the extended real number line.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Since a real number r can be interpreted as the interval [*r*, *r*], intervals and real numbers can be freely combined.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Consider the calculation of a person's body mass index (BMI).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] BMI is calculated as a person's body weight in kilograms divided by the square of their height in meters.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Suppose a person uses a scale that has a precision of one kilogram, where intermediate values cannot be discerned, and the true weight is rounded to the nearest whole number.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For example, 79.6 kg and 80.3 kg are indistinguishable, as the scale can only display values to the nearest kilogram.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] It is unlikely that when the scale reads 80 kg, the person has a weight of *exactly* 80.0 kg.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Thus, the scale displaying 80 kg indicates a weight between 79.5 kg and 80.5 kg, or the interval [79.5, 80.5).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The BMI of a man who weighs 80 kg and is 1.80 m tall is approximately 24.7.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A weight of 79.5 kg and the same height yields a BMI of 24.537, while a weight of 80.5 kg yields 24.846.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Since the body mass is continuous and always increasing for all values within the specified weight interval, the true BMI must lie within the interval [24.537, 24.846].
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Since the entire interval is less than 25, which is the cutoff between normal and excessive weight, it can be concluded with certainty that the man is of normal weight.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The error in this example does not affect the conclusion (normal weight), but this is not generally true.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] If the man were slightly heavier, the BMI's range may include the cutoff value of 25.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In such a case, the scale's precision would be insufficient to make a definitive conclusion.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The range of BMI examples could be reported as [24.5, 24.9] since this interval is a superset of the calculated interval.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The range could not, however, be reported as [24.6, 24.8], as the interval does not contain possible BMI values.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Height and body weight both affect the value of the BMI.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Though the example above only considered variation in weight, height is also subject to uncertainty.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Height measurements in meters are usually rounded to the nearest centimeter: a recorded measurement of 1.79 meters represents a height in the interval [1.785, 1.795).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Since the BMI uniformly increases with respect to weight and decreases with respect to height, the error interval can be calculated by substituting the lowest and highest values of each interval, and then selecting the lowest and highest results as boundaries.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In this case, the man may have normal weight or be overweight; the weight and height measurements were insufficiently precise to make a definitive conclusion.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In other words, it is the set of all possible values of *x* ∗ *y*, where x and y are in their corresponding intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] If ∗ is monotone for each operand on the intervals, which is the case for the four basic arithmetic operations (except division when the denominator contains zero), the extreme values occur at the endpoints of the operand intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The last case loses useful information about the exclusion of (⁠1/*y*1⁠, ⁠1/*y*2⁠).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] More generally, when working with discontinuous functions, it is sometimes useful to do the calculation with so-called *multi-intervals* of the form ⋃*i* [*ai*, *bi*].
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The corresponding *multi-interval arithmetic* maintains a set of (usually disjoint) intervals and also provides for overlapping intervals to unite.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval multiplication often only requires two multiplications.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The multiplication can be interpreted as the area of a rectangle with varying edges.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The result interval covers all possible areas, from the smallest to the largest.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] With the help of these definitions, it is already possible to calculate the range of simple functions, such as *f*(*a*,*b*,*x*) = *ax* + *b*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] To shorten the notation of intervals, brackets can be used.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] [*x*] ≡ [*x*1, *x*2] can be used to represent an interval.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Note that in such a compact notation, [*x*] should not be confused between a single-point interval [*x*1, *x*1] and a general interval.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval functions beyond the four basic operators may also be defined.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For monotonic functions in one variable, the range of values is simple to compute.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For even powers, the range of values being considered is important and needs to be dealt with before doing any multiplication.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For example, *x**n* for *x* ∈ [−1, 1] should produce the interval [0, 1] for even *n* ∈ ℕ.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] But if [−1, 1]*n* is taken by repeating interval multiplication of form [−1, 1] · [−1, 1] · ⋯ · [−1, 1] then the result is [−1, 1], wider than necessary.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] More generally one can say that, for piecewise monotonic functions, it is sufficient to consider the endpoints *x*1, *x*2 of an interval, together with the so-called *critical points* within the interval, being those points where the monotonicity of the function changes direction.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For the sine and cosine functions, the critical points are respectively at (*n* + ⁠1/2⁠)*π* and *nπ*, for *n* ∈ ℤ.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Thus, only up to five points within an interval need to be considered, as the resulting interval is [−1, 1] if the interval includes at least two extrema.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For sine and cosine, only the endpoints need full evaluation, as the critical points lead to easily pre-calculated values—namely −1, 0, and 1.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In general, it may not be easy to find such a simple description of the output interval for many functions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] But it may still be possible to extend functions to interval arithmetic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] This definition of the interval extension does not give a precise result.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Tighter extensions are desirable, though the relative costs of calculation and imprecision should be considered; in this case, [*f*] should be chosen as it gives the tightest possible result.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Given a real expression, its *natural interval extension* is achieved by using the interval extensions of each of its subexpressions, functions, and operators.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] for some **y** ∈ [**x**], where D*i* *f*(**y**) is the ith order differential of f at the point **y** and [*r*] is an interval extension of the *Taylor remainder*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Usually **y** is chosen to be the midpoint of the interval and uses the natural interval extension to assess the remainder.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The special case of the Taylor interval extension of degree *k* = 0 is also referred to as the *mean value form*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] An interval can be defined as a set of points within a specified distance of the center, and this definition can be extended from real numbers to complex numbers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Another extension defines intervals as rectangles in the complex plane.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] As is the case with computing with real numbers, computing with complex numbers involves uncertain data.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] So, given the fact that an interval number is a real closed interval and a complex number is an ordered pair of real numbers, there is no reason to limit the application of interval arithmetic to the measure of uncertainties in computations with real numbers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic can thus be extended, via complex interval numbers, to determine regions of uncertainty in computing with complex numbers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] One can either define complex interval arithmetic using rectangles or using disks, both with their respective advantages and disadvantages.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The basic algebraic operations for real interval numbers (real closed intervals) can be extended to complex numbers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] It is therefore not surprising that complex interval arithmetic is similar to, but not the same as, ordinary complex arithmetic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] It can be shown that, as is the case with real interval arithmetic, there is no distributivity between the addition and multiplication of complex interval numbers except for certain special cases, and inverse elements do not always exist for complex interval numbers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Two other useful properties of ordinary complex arithmetic fail to hold in complex interval arithmetic: the additive and multiplicative properties, of ordinary complex conjugates, do not hold for complex interval conjugates.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic can be extended, in an analogous manner, to other multidimensional number systems such as quaternions and octonions, but with the expense that we have to sacrifice other useful properties of ordinary arithmetic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The methods of classical numerical analysis cannot be transferred one-to-one into interval-valued algorithms, as dependencies between numerical values are usually not taken into account.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] To work effectively in a real-life implementation, intervals must be compatible with floating point computing.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The earlier operations were based on exact arithmetic, but in general fast numerical solution methods may not be available for it.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Where the same calculation is done with single-digit precision, the result would normally be [0.2, 0.9].
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] But [0.2, 0.9] ⊉ [0.16, 0.88], so this approach would contradict the basic principles of interval arithmetic, as a part of the domain of *f*([0.1, 0.8], [0.06, 0.08]) would be lost.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Instead, the outward-rounded solution [0.1, 0.9] is used.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The standard IEEE 754 for binary floating-point arithmetic also sets out procedures for the implementation of rounding.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] An IEEE 754 compliant system allows programmers to round to the nearest floating-point number; alternatives are rounding towards zero (truncating), rounding toward positive infinity (rounding up), or rounding towards negative infinity (rounding down).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The required *external rounding* for interval arithmetic can thus be achieved by changing the rounding settings of the processor in the calculation of the upper limit (up) and lower limit (down).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Alternatively, an appropriate small interval [*ε*1, *ε*2] can be added.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic has also been implemented using arbitrary-precision floating-point arithmetic, where the precision is much higher (but still finite, hence still requires rounding).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Larger arbitrary-precision numbers are slow to compute and take a significant amount of space to store.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A variant of interval arithmetic called **ball arithmetic** stores a high-precision midpoint and a low-precision radius instead of two high-precision lower and upper bounds as in conventional (infimum–supremum) interval arithmetic, reducing the cost of computation.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The so-called *dependency problem* is a major obstacle to the application of interval arithmetic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Although interval methods can determine the range of elementary arithmetic operations and functions very accurately, this is not always true with more complicated functions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] If an interval occurs several times in a calculation using parameters, and each occurrence is taken independently, then this can lead to an unwanted expansion of the resulting intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] As an illustration, take the function f defined by *f*(*x*) = *x*2 + *x*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The values of this function over the interval [−1, 1] are [−⁠1/4⁠, 2].
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] which is slightly larger; we have instead calculated the infimum and supremum of the function *h*(*x*, *y*) = *x*2 + *y* over *x*, *y* ∈ [−1, 1].
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In general, it can be shown that the exact range of values can be achieved, if each variable appears only once and if f is continuous inside the box.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] However, not every function can be rewritten this way.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The dependency of the problem causing over-estimation of the value range can go as far as covering a large range, preventing more meaningful conclusions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] An additional increase in the range stems from the solution of areas that do not take the form of an interval vector.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] is precisely the line between the points (−1, −1) and (1, 1).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Using interval methods results in the unit square, [−1, 1] × [−1, 1].
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A linear interval system consists of a matrix interval extension [**A**] ∈ [ℝ]*n* × *m* and an interval vector [**b**] ∈ [ℝ]*n*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For quadratic systems (in other words, for *n* = *m*) there can be such an interval vector [**x**], which covers all possible solutions, found simply with the interval Gauss method.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] This replaces the numerical operations, in that the linear algebra method known as Gaussian elimination becomes its interval version.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] However, since this method uses the interval entities [**A**] and [**b**] repeatedly in the calculation, it can produce poor results for some problems.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Hence using the result of the interval-valued Gauss only provides first rough estimates, since although it contains the entire solution set, it also has a large area outside it.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A rough solution [**x**] can often be improved by an interval version of the Gauss–Seidel method.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] can be determined by the variable xi if the division ⁠1/[*aii*]⁠ is allowed.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] and so the vector [**x**] by each element.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] If one chooses, for example, **M** = **A**−1 for the central matrix **A** ∈ [**A**], then **M** · [**A**] is an outer extension of the identity matrix.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] These methods only work well if the widths of the intervals occurring are sufficiently small.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For wider intervals, it can be useful to use an interval-linear system on finite (albeit large) real number equivalent linear systems.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] If all the matrices **A** ∈ [**A**] are invertible, it is sufficient to consider all possible combinations (upper and lower) of the endpoints occurring in the intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The resulting problems can be resolved using conventional numerical methods.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic is still used to determine rounding errors.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] This is only suitable for systems of smaller dimension, since with a fully occupied *n* × *n* matrix, 2*n*2 real matrices need to be inverted, with 2*n* vectors for the right-hand side.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] This approach was developed by Jiri Rohn and is still being developed.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] An interval variant of Newton's method for finding the zeros in an interval vector [**x**] can be derived from the average value extension.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] An outer estimate of [*Jf*]([**x**])−1 · *f*(**y**) can be determined using linear methods.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In contrast to traditional methods, the interval method approaches the result by containing the zeros.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] This guarantees that the result produces all zeros in the initial range.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Conversely, it proves that no zeros of f were in the initial range [**x**] if a Newton step produces the empty set.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The method converges on all zeros in the starting region.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Division by zero can lead to the separation of distinct zeros, though the separation may not be complete; it can be complemented by the bisection method.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] As an example, consider the function *f*(*x*) = *x*2 − 2, the starting range [*x*] = [−2, 2], and the point *y* = 0.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] These converge to arbitrarily small intervals around −√2 and +√2 respectively.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The interval Newton method can also be used with *thick functions* such as *g*(*x*) = *x*2 − [2, 3], which would in any case have interval results.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The result then produces intervals containing [−√3, −√2] ∪ [√2, √3].
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The various interval methods deliver conservative results as dependencies between the sizes of different interval extensions are not taken into account.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] However, the dependency problem becomes less significant for narrower intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Since [*f*]([**x**]) is often a genuine superset of the right-hand side, this usually leads to an improved estimate.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] If the result is still not suitable then further gradual subdivision is possible.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A cover of 2*r* intervals results from r divisions of vector elements, substantially increasing the computation costs.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] With very wide intervals, it can be helpful to split all intervals into several subintervals with a constant (and smaller) width, a method known as *mincing*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] This then avoids the calculations for intermediate bisection steps.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Both methods are only suitable for problems of low dimension.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic can be used in various areas (such as set inversion, motion planning, set estimation, or stability analysis) to treat estimates with no exact numerical value.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic is used with error analysis, to control rounding errors arising from each calculation.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The advantage of interval arithmetic is that after each operation there is an interval that reliably includes the true result.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval analysis adds to rather than substituting for traditional methods for error reduction, such as pivoting.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Parameters for which no exact figures can be allocated often arise during the simulation of technical and physical processes.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The production process of technical components allows certain tolerances, so some parameters fluctuate within intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In addition, many fundamental constants are not known precisely.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] If the behavior of such a system affected by tolerances satisfies, for example, *f*(*x*, *p*) = 0, for **p** ∈ [**p**] and unknown **x** then the set of possible solutions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] This provides an alternative to traditional propagation of error analysis.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Unlike point methods, such as Monte Carlo simulation, interval arithmetic methodology ensures that no part of the solution area can be overlooked.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] However, the result is always a worst-case analysis for the distribution of error, as other probability-based distributions are not considered.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic can also be used with affiliation functions for fuzzy quantities as they are used in fuzzy logic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Apart from the strict statements *x* ∈ [*x*] and *x* ∉ [*x*], intermediate values are also possible, to which real numbers *μ* ∈ [0, 1] are assigned.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] *μ* = 1 corresponds to definite membership while *μ* = 0 is non-membership.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A distribution function assigns uncertainty, which can be understood as a further interval.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For *fuzzy arithmetic* only a finite number of discrete affiliation stages *μi* ∈ [0, 1] are considered.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The form of such a distribution for an indistinct value can then be represented by a sequence of intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The interval [*x*(*i*)] corresponds exactly to the fluctuation range for the stage *μi*.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] and can be calculated by interval methods.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The value [*y*(1)] corresponds to the result of an interval calculation.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Warwick Tucker used interval arithmetic in order to solve the 14th of Smale's problems, that is, to show that the Lorenz attractor is a strange attractor.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Thomas Hales used interval arithmetic in order to solve the Kepler conjecture.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The Fast Library for Number Theory website lists several uses of the FLINT/Arb ball arithmetic library in published papers and preprints.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Interval arithmetic is not a completely new phenomenon in mathematics; it has appeared several times under different names in the course of history.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For example, Archimedes calculated lower and upper bounds ⁠223/71⁠ < *π* < ⁠22/7⁠ in the 3rd century BC.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Actual calculation with intervals has neither been as popular as other numerical techniques nor been completely forgotten.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Rules for calculating with intervals and other subsets of the real numbers were published in a 1931 work by Rosalind Cicely Young.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Arithmetic work on range numbers to improve the reliability of digital systems was then published in a 1951 textbook on linear algebra by Paul S.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Dwyer; intervals were used to measure rounding errors associated with floating-point numbers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A comprehensive paper on interval algebra in numerical analysis was published by Teruo Sunaga (1958).
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The birth of modern interval arithmetic was marked by the appearance of the book *Interval Analysis* by Ramon E.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] He had the idea in spring 1958, and a year later he published an article about computer interval arithmetic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Its merit was that starting with a simple principle, it provided a general method for automated error analysis, not just errors resulting from rounding.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Independently in 1956, Mieczyslaw Warmus suggested formulae for calculations with intervals, though Moore found the first non-trivial applications.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In the following twenty years, German groups of researchers carried out pioneering work around Ulrich W.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Kulisch and Götz Alefeld at the University of Karlsruhe and later also at the Bergische University of Wuppertal.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] For example, Karl Nickel explored more effective implementations, while improved containment procedures for the solution set of systems of equations were due to Arnold Neumaier among others.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Hansen dealt with interval extensions for linear equations and then provided crucial contributions to global optimization, including what is now known as Hansen's method, perhaps the most widely used interval algorithm.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In 1988, Rudolf Lohner developed Fortran-based software for reliable solutions for initial value problems using ordinary differential equations.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The journal *Reliable Computing* (originally *Interval Computations*) has been published since the 1990s, dedicated to the reliability of computer-aided computations.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Baker Kearfott, in addition to his work on global optimization, has contributed significantly to the unification of notation and terminology used in interval arithmetic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In recent years work has concentrated in particular on the estimation of preimages of parameterized functions and to robust control theory by the COPRIN working group of INRIA in Sophia Antipolis in France.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] There are many software packages that permit the development of numerical applications using interval arithmetic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] These are usually provided in the form of program libraries.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] There are also C++ and Fortran compilers that handle interval data types and suitable operations as a language extension, so interval arithmetic is supported directly.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Since 1967, *Extensions for Scientific Computation* (XSC) have been developed in the University of Karlsruhe for various programming languages, such as C++, Fortran, and Pascal.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The first platform was a Zuse Z23, for which a new interval data type with appropriate elementary operators was made available.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] There followed in 1976, Pascal-SC, a Pascal variant on a Zilog Z80 that it made possible to create fast, complicated routines for automated result verification.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Then came the Fortran 77-based ACRITH-XSC for the System/370 architecture (FORTRAN-SC), which was later delivered by IBM.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Starting from 1991 one could produce code for C compilers with Pascal-XSC; a year later the C++ class library supported C-XSC on many different computer systems.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In 1997, all XSC variants were made available under the GNU General Public License.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] At the beginning of 2000, C-XSC 2.0 was released under the leadership of the working group for scientific computation at the Bergische University of Wuppertal to correspond to the improved C++ standard.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Another C++-class library was created in 1993 at the Hamburg University of Technology called *Profil/BIAS* (Programmer's Runtime Optimized Fast Interval Library, Basic Interval Arithmetic), which made the usual interval operations more user-friendly.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] It emphasized the efficient use of hardware, portability, and independence of a particular presentation of intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The Boost collection of C++ libraries contains a template class for intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Its authors are aiming to have interval arithmetic in the standard C++ language.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The Frink programming language has an implementation of interval arithmetic that handles arbitrary-precision numbers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Programs written in Frink can use intervals without rewriting or recompilation.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] GAOL is another C++ interval arithmetic library that is unique in that it offers the relational interval operators used in interval constraint programming.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The Moore library is an efficient implementation of interval arithmetic in C++.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] It provides intervals with endpoints of arbitrary precision and is based on the *concepts* feature of C++.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] The Julia programming language has an implementation of interval arithmetics along with high-level features, such as root-finding (for both real and complex-valued functions) and interval constraint programming, via the ValidatedNumerics.jl package.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] In addition, computer algebra systems, such as Euler Mathematical Toolbox, FriCAS, Maple, Mathematica, Maxima and MuPAD, can handle intervals.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A Matlab extension *Intlab* builds on BLAS routines, and the toolbox b4m makes a Profil/BIAS interface.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A library for the functional language OCaml was written in assembly language and C.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] MPFI is a library for arbitrary precision interval arithmetic; it is written in C and is based on MPFR.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A standard for interval arithmetic, IEEE Std 1788-2015, has been approved in June 2015.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Two reference implementations are freely available.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] These have been developed by members of the standard's working group: The libieeep1788 library for C++, and the interval package for GNU Octave.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] A minimal subset of the standard, IEEE Std 1788.1-2017, has been approved in December 2017 and published in February 2018.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] It should be easier to implement and may speed production of implementations.
[src:abstract-interpretation/interval-arithmetic] Several international conferences or workshops take place every year in the world.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A **lattice** is an abstract structure studied in the mathematical subdisciplines of order theory and abstract algebra.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] It consists of a partially ordered set in which every pair of elements has a unique supremum (also called a least upper bound or join) and a unique infimum (also called a greatest lower bound or meet).
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] An example is given by the power set of a set, partially ordered by inclusion, for which the supremum is the union and the infimum is the intersection.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Another example is given by the natural numbers, partially ordered by divisibility, for which the supremum is the least common multiple and the infimum is the greatest common divisor.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Lattices can also be characterized as algebraic structures satisfying certain axiomatic identities.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Since the two definitions are equivalent, lattice theory draws on both order theory and universal algebra.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The class of lattices can be generalized to semilattices, and some notable subclasses of lattices are Heyting algebras, Boolean algebras, distributive lattices, and geometric lattices (matroids).
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] These *lattice-like* structures all admit order-theoretic as well as algebraic descriptions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The sub-field that studies lattices is called **lattice theory**.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A lattice can be defined either order-theoretically as a partially ordered set, or as an algebraic structure.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A partially ordered set (poset) $(L,\leq )$ is called a **lattice** if it is both a join- and a meet-semilattice, i.e. each two-element subset $\{a,b\}\subseteq L$ has a join (i.e. least upper bound, denoted by $a\vee b$ ) and dually a meet (i.e. greatest lower bound, denoted by $a\wedge b$ ).
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] This definition makes $\,\wedge \,$ and $\,\vee \,$ binary operations.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] It follows by an induction argument that every non-empty finite subset of a lattice has a least upper bound and a greatest lower bound.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] With additional assumptions, further conclusions may be possible; see *Completeness (order theory)* for more discussion of this subject.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] That article also discusses how one may rephrase the above definition in terms of the existence of suitable Galois connections between related partially ordered sets—an approach of special interest for the category theoretic approach to lattices, and for formal concept analysis.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Given a subset of a lattice, $H\subseteq L,$ meet and join restrict to partial functions – they are undefined if their value is not in the subset $H.$ The resulting structure on H is called a **partial lattice**.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In addition to this extrinsic definition as a subset of some other algebraic structure (a lattice), a partial lattice can also be intrinsically defined as a set with two partial binary operations satisfying certain axioms.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The following two identities are also usually regarded as axioms, even though they follow from the two absorption laws taken together.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] These axioms assert that both $(L,\vee )$ and $(L,\wedge )$ are semilattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The absorption laws, the only axioms above in which both meet and join appear, distinguish a lattice from an arbitrary pair of semilattice structures and assure that the two semilattices interact appropriately.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In particular, each semilattice is the dual of the other.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The absorption laws can be viewed as a requirement that the meet and join semilattices define the same partial order.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] An order-theoretic lattice gives rise to the two binary operations $\vee$ and $\wedge .$ Since the commutative, associative and absorption laws can easily be verified for these operations, they make $(L,\vee ,\wedge )$ into a lattice in the algebraic sense.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Since the two definitions of a lattice are equivalent, one may freely invoke aspects of either definition in any way that suits the purpose at hand.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] It can be shown that a partially ordered set is a bounded lattice if and only if every finite set of elements (including the empty set) has a join and a meet.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Every lattice can be embedded into a bounded lattice by adding a greatest and a least element.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Lattices have some connections to the family of group-like algebraic structures.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Because meet and join both commute and associate, a lattice can be viewed as consisting of two commutative semigroups having the same domain.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For a bounded lattice, these semigroups are in fact commutative monoids.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The absorption law is the only defining identity that is peculiar to lattice theory.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A bounded lattice can also be thought of as a commutative rig without the distributive axiom.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] By commutativity, associativity and idempotence one can think of join and meet as operations on non-empty finite sets, rather than on pairs of elements.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In a bounded lattice the join and meet of the empty set can also be defined (as 0 and $1,$ respectively).
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] This makes bounded lattices somewhat more natural than general lattices, and many authors require all lattices to be bounded.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The algebraic interpretation of lattices plays an essential role in universal algebra.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Further examples of lattices are given for each of the additional properties discussed below.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Most partially ordered sets are not lattices, including the following.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The appropriate notion of a morphism between two lattices flows easily from the above algebraic definition.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Thus f is a homomorphism of the two underlying semilattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] When lattices with more structure are considered, the morphisms should "respect" the extra structure, too.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In the order-theoretic formulation, these conditions just state that a homomorphism of lattices is a function preserving binary meets and joins.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For bounded lattices, preservation of least and greatest elements is just preservation of join and meet of the empty set.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Any homomorphism of lattices is necessarily monotone with respect to the associated ordering relation; see Limit preserving function.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The converse is not true: monotonicity by no means implies the required preservation of meets and joins (see Pic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] 9), although an order-preserving bijection is a homomorphism if its inverse is also order-preserving.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Given the standard definition of isomorphisms as invertible morphisms, a **lattice isomorphism** is just a bijective lattice homomorphism.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Similarly, a **lattice endomorphism** is a lattice homomorphism from a lattice to itself, and a **lattice automorphism** is a bijective lattice endomorphism.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Lattices and their homomorphisms form a category.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] We now introduce a number of important properties that lead to interesting special classes of lattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] One, boundedness, has already been discussed.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A poset is called a **complete lattice** if *all* its subsets have both a join and a meet.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In particular, every complete lattice is a bounded lattice.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] While bounded lattice homomorphisms in general preserve only finite joins and meets, complete lattice homomorphisms are required to preserve arbitrary joins and meets.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Every poset that is a complete semilattice is also a complete lattice.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Related to this result is the interesting phenomenon that there are various competing notions of homomorphism for this class of posets, depending on whether they are seen as complete lattices, complete join-semilattices, complete meet-semilattices, or as join-complete or meet-complete lattices.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] "Partial lattice" is not the opposite of "complete lattice" – rather, "partial lattice", "lattice", and "complete lattice" are increasingly restrictive definitions.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A **conditionally complete lattice** is a lattice in which every *nonempty* subset *that has an upper bound* has a join (that is, a least upper bound).
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Such lattices provide the most direct generalization of the completeness axiom of the real numbers.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A conditionally complete lattice is either a complete lattice, or a complete lattice without its maximum element $1,$ its minimum element $0,$ or both.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A lattice that satisfies the first or, equivalently (as it turns out), the second axiom, is called a **distributive lattice**.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The only non-distributive lattices with fewer than 6 elements are called M3 and N5; they are shown in Pictures 10 and 11, respectively.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A lattice is distributive if and only if it does not have a sublattice isomorphic to M3 or N5.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Each distributive lattice is isomorphic to a lattice of sets (with union and intersection as join and meet, respectively).
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For an overview of stronger notions of distributivity that are appropriate for complete lattices and that are used to define more special classes of lattices such as frames and completely distributive lattices, see distributivity in order theory.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For some applications the distributivity condition is too strong, and the following weaker property is often useful.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A lattice is modular if and only if it does not have a sublattice isomorphic to N5 (shown in Pic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Besides distributive lattices, examples of modular lattices are the lattice of submodules of a module (hence *modular*), the lattice of two-sided ideals of a ring, and the lattice of normal subgroups of a group.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The set of first-order terms with the ordering "is more specific than" is a non-modular lattice used in automated reasoning.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A finite lattice is modular if and only if it is both upper and lower semimodular.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A lattice is called lower semimodular if its dual is semimodular.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For finite lattices this means that the previous conditions hold with $\vee$ and $\wedge$ exchanged, "covers" exchanged with "is covered by", and inequalities reversed.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In domain theory, it is natural to seek to approximate the elements in a partial order by "much simpler" elements.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] This leads to the class of continuous posets, consisting of posets where every element can be obtained as the supremum of a directed set of elements that are way-below the element.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] If one can additionally restrict these to the compact elements of a poset for obtaining these directed sets, then the poset is even algebraic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Both of these classes have interesting properties.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For example, continuous lattices can be characterized as algebraic structures (with infinitary operations) satisfying certain identities.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] While such a characterization is not known for algebraic lattices, they can be described "syntactically" via Scott information systems.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Let L be a bounded lattice with greatest element 1 and least element 0.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In general, some elements of a bounded lattice might not have a complement, and others might have more than one complement.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For example, the set $\{0,1/2,1\}$ with its usual ordering is a bounded lattice, and ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ does not have a complement.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In the bounded lattice N5, the element a has two complements, viz. b and c (see Pic.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A bounded lattice for which every element has a complement is called a complemented lattice.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] A complemented lattice that is also distributive is a Boolean algebra.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For a distributive lattice, the complement of $x,$ when it exists, is unique.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] In the case that the complement is unique, we write ${\textstyle \lnot x=y}$ and equivalently, ${\textstyle \lnot y=x.}$ The corresponding unary operation over $L,$ called complementation, introduces an analogue of logical negation into lattice theory.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Heyting algebras are an example of distributive lattices where some members might be lacking complements.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] If for any pair, x and $y,$ where $x<y,$ all maximal chains from x to y have the same length, then the lattice is said to satisfy the **Jordan–Dedekind chain condition**.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Any set X may be used to generate the **free semilattice** $FX.$ The free semilattice is defined to consist of all of the finite subsets of $X,$ with the semilattice operation given by ordinary set union.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The free semilattice has the universal property.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] For the **free lattice** over a set $X,$ Whitman gave a construction based on polynomials over X 's members.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Any (usually multielement) set X may also be used to define a **flat lattice**, the least lattice in which the set's elements are incomparable or, equivalently, the rank-3 lattice where X is exactly the set of elements of intermediate rank.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] We now define some order-theoretic notions of importance to lattice theory.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] However, many sources and mathematical communities use the term "atomic" to mean "atomistic" as defined above.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] The notions of ideals and the dual notion of filters refer to particular kinds of subsets of a partially ordered set, and are therefore important for lattice theory.
[src:abstract-interpretation/lattice-order] Details can be found in the respective entries.
